<h1>About DairyPlant Atlas</h1>
<p class="lede">
  An educational lookup for U.S. dairy plants. We take the codes
  printed on cartons, tubs, and wedges and tell you the real facility
  behind them — plus what other brands come out of the same plant.
</p>

<h2>What you can do here</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Look up a code.</strong> Type the stamp from your package — like <code>55-372</code> — into the search bar and we'll show you the plant.</li>
  <li><strong>Search by brand or company.</strong> Type "Cabot" or "fairlife" and we'll show the plants that make those products.</li>
  <li><strong>Browse the map.</strong> See every plant we've geocoded, by state and category.</li>
  <li><strong>Trace recall history.</strong> For journalists and researchers — every FDA dairy enforcement record, linked to plants where possible.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Where the data comes from</h2>
<ul>
  <li><a href="https://www.fda.gov/food/milk-guidance-documents-regulatory-information/interstate-milk-shippers-list" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FDA Interstate Milk Shippers List</a> — Grade A fluid and cultured plants.</li>
  <li>USDA AMS Approved Dairy Plants — manufactured products (cheese, butter, dry milk, frozen desserts).</li>
  <li><a href="https://open.fda.gov/apis/food/enforcement/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">openFDA Food Enforcement API</a> — recall records.</li>
  <li>Hand-curated brand-to-plant mappings, each with a source citation.</li>
</ul>

<h2>About the codes</h2>
<p>
  Every dairy plant in the U.S. is registered with one or more federal
  agencies. The code stamped on your package usually starts with a
  state-FIPS number (the first two digits) followed by the plant's
  number inside that state. <code>55-372</code> means "Wisconsin, plant
  372" — which happens to be Westby Cooperative Creamery.
</p>
<p>
  Some plants appear under multiple code systems. A Grade A fluid
  facility shows up in the FDA IMS list with one number, while its
  manufactured-cheese line may carry a different USDA number. We
  surface both when we can.
</p>

<h2>How sure are we?</h2>
<p>
  Where data comes straight from a federal database (IMS, USDA AMS,
  openFDA), it's as authoritative as those sources are. For
  brand-to-plant mappings, every row carries a citation — usually the
  manufacturer's own published statement or an FDA recall notice that
  identified the producing plant by code. We mark our confidence as
  high, medium, or low so you can judge for yourself.
</p>

<h2>Found something wrong?</h2>
<p>
  Email <a href="mailto:brunndairy88@gmail.com?subject=DairyPlant%20Atlas%20correction">brunndairy88@gmail.com</a>
